## Methods
The list of the used technology stack, tools, and systems includes but is not limited to: TypeScript, Rust, Tauri v2, Temurin JDK 8/16/17/21, Windows 10, and NixOS. To examine the MultiMC patch system, I proceeded in several steps. First, I collected all available at the moment of writing patch index files (i.e. `net.minecraft`, `net.minecraftforge`) and built an approximate representation of the response type. I did the same action for specific versions of each patch using the latest version. Next, I reviewed the blog posts about Minecraft launching from Lin [3] and Ryan [4]. I then tried to make a mental model of a Minecraft launching process while finding similarities between Mojang API and Prism Launcher meta API. Finally, I started the development where many horrifying things beyond my comprehension awaited me.

## Results and Discussion
The MultiMC patch system is a complex, yet convenient way to manage Minecraft launch with various mod loaders support. If one manages the MultiMC patch system in their code in a proper way, they will not need to write a code to handle each patch separately since patches are standardized.
### How to think of MultiMC patches
Before we start coding, we should understand what to expect from patches.

As stated by Ryan [4], the Prism Launcher meta server is generating JSON patches from multiple sources. Those sources can have completely different formats of library and asset structures. Bringing such inconsistencies to one consistent response format is challenging. Thus, we will stumble upon many minor inconveniences when handling MultiMC patches.

